bout 40 miles west of his birthplace in the village of Forst. It’s an area famed for wine-growing, and the wine culture – grape-growing, wine-making, and wine consumption -- is a central theme in the community’s day-to-day life. It’s even part of the Blanz family: his wife Anja grew up on a winery in Forst and her sister and brother-in-law still run the family business today.\n\nIt’s no surprise that wine-related topics run a close second to technology when Josef talks about his personal interests. “That is a must in our village,” he said. “I am not really an expert or connoisseur, but I like wine-tasting and enjoy learning more and more about wine.”\n\nHis ideal day? “Enjoying the Forster Weinfest on a nice, warm summer day with family and friends while strolling between booths and wineries enjoying good food, listening to good live music, talking with people I know well and not so well and, of course, drinking some good wine.”\n\nThe father of three children ranging in ages from 13 to 9, Josef makes sure all sorts of things are connected in his home. He set up a large touchscreen in the kitchen to control everything. He checks on his house and change settings while traveling and opens the door and gate from his phone or laptop.\n<h3>Hooked on BASIC as a teen-ager</h3>\nJosef originally set out follow in the footsteps of his father, a civil engineer. He changed career directions when, as a teen-ager, he tried his hand at BASIC programming on his father’s work computer. He was hooked, and wound up earning a degree in electrical engineering. He studied engineering at the University of Kaiserslautern, which at the time was home to one of the location of one of the world’s leading research teams on CDMA. While still an undergraduate, Josef designed a Viterbi Equalizer for the group, which led to the offer of a post-graduate position with an option to get a Ph. D., which he accepted.\n\nOne of his mentors at the university was Dr. Paul Walter Baier, one of the few CDMA experts in Germany at that time and an acquaintance of Qualcomm co-founder Andrew Viterbi.\n\n“He was a tough guy,” Josef said of Baier. “He taught me that you need to keep on working on a problem until you really get to the bottom of it and don’t give up halfway.”\n\nJosef joined Qualcomm in 1998, just as the company was trying to crack the 3GPP market and ramping up efforts to implement MTS chips. He recalls it was an uphill battle for Qualcomm to be accepted as a solid contributor interested in producing effective technology. But by a decade later, Qualcomm had become a leader in 3GPP technology.\n<h3>Diverse approach fits Standards group</h3>\nOver the years, he said the emphasis of the standards group has shifted.\n\n“Initially the focus was on 3GPP and 3GPP2, but today the set of groups we attend and work with is much more diverse,” he said.\n\nJosef is excited to be involved with wireless technology that has made it easier to stay in touch with family and friends from almost any place.\n\n“Without wireless technology I would have a very hard time traveling as much as I do,” he said. “It helps in so many situations to talk to family, to be reachable for business, to stay connected, do email, conference calls, get information off the web, all while on the go.”\n\nHis Standards project recently reached a significant milestone − Completion of a first release of specifications for M2M communications based on an M2M Service layer produced within oneM2M, a global partnership of SDOs created to support the M2M/IoT concept.\n\n“This standard has the potential to become a key enabler for larger scale M2M/IoT deployments across a number of different industry segments,” Josef said. “It may allow Qualcomm to develop products that could be sold into various industry segments or so-called verticals without the need for vertical-specific product specializations.”\n<h3>Building success through oneM2M</h3>\nJosef was a key player in the creation of oneM2M, and helped get a Qualcomm consultant Peter Nurse selected as chair of the oneM2M Technical Plenary, a move that he believes will help speed up progress in oneM2M and ensure that Qualcomm maintains a leadership role in the organization.\n\nBut as M2M/IoT gets bigger, there are more challenges. “Almost every other week you can see press releases about yet another organization that wants to cover the whole breadth and depth of M2m/IOT.\n\nThat fragmentation makes for competing groups, primarily pushed by Qualcomm competitors. The key to solving this is consolidation and a reasonable work split.\n\n“We have to stay on top of which organizations are really relevant and keep on consolidating and aligning across those in order to avoid overlap and enable interworking,” he said.\n\nPart of his challenge is overcoming skepticism from other companies when Qualcomm gets involved with a new standards organization.\n\n“Many other stakeholders suspect that we are only interested in pushing our own IPR,” he said. That sort of test arose recently in the oneM2M group when some features Qualcomm wanted specified as mandatory were watered down.\n\n“The best way to deal with such a situation is to focus on making our preferred solutions technically better and specify them in a precise manner so that using them in an implementation provides added value,” Josef said.\n\nIt takes time, he said, but after a while, individual delegates realize that Qualcomm representatives are actually quite reasonable and begin to trust that the company is interested only in designing a technically sound and proper system.\n\nHis immediate focus is on incorporating the technology specified in oneM2M with the technology Qualcomm promotes in the open source-based AllSeen Alliance and on promoting the overall value of oneM2M technology. Those efforts, Josef said, will help Qualcomm position its products for the M2M/IoT markets to make them the best choice for implementers.\n<h3>Setting standards for the future</h3>\nBlanz said it’s rewarding to work with a diverse group of people both within Qualcomm and externally.\n\n“Through the work in international and global standardization bodies, you get to know very different styles of communicating and ways of working with each other,” he said. “You get the rare opportunity to constantly improve your understanding of different cultures and mentalities. This is a very valuable skill that cannot be learned in many other jobs.”\n\nHe also appreciates the opportunity to be part of an effort that is shaping the future of M2M/IoT technology and affecting the lives of today’s generations and generations to come.\n\n“It is motivating to see – sometimes over the span of quite a few years – that a few things you have been dealing with in standards actually make it into products and ultimately affect the way we live.”\n\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][image_with_animation image_url="157" animation="Fade In" img_link_target="_self"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row type="in_container" bg_position="left top" bg_repeat="no-repeat" scene_position="center" text_color="dark" text_align="left" id="profile2"][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]\n<h2>Rolf De Vegt</h2>\n[/vc_column_text][vc_column_text]Curabitur in ligula elit. Aenean a lorem feugiat felis lacinia blandit. Proin lacus risus, placerat vehicula augue eget, posuere pharetra lacus. Donec egestas id ex vel dignissim. Suspendisse maximus massa nec metus rutrum condimentum. Vivamus libero ligula, semper id nisi condimentum, porta gravida urna. Cras dictum euismod vehicula.\n\nMaecenas volutpat pharetra euismod. Praesent lacinia sapien elit, quis egestas tellus sodales sit amet. Praesent vel lorem quis nulla feugiat scelerisque. Fusce tortor dui, posuere eu malesuada eget, euismod id nulla. Fusce consectetur urna sit amet.\n\nCurabitur vitae sapien vehicula, lobortis purus nec, hendrerit lectus. Donec et gravida ipsum. Nunc vitae turpis eu risus consequat mattis. Integer sit amet vulputate nisl. Cras fringilla nulla eget velit bibendum scelerisque. Nunc diam arcu, interdum ut rhoncus eu, elementum at nisi. Vestibulum odio felis, porttitor in tortor quis, placerat dapibus est. Phasellus vel erat eu elit finibus pretium sed id lorem. Vivamus id tellus in diam luctus lobortis ac sodales erat. Sed tellus sapien, scelerisque vel fringilla eu, ornare vel arcu. Duis posuere condimentum ante vel feugiat. Maecenas ullamcorper dolor nulla, quis consectetur est porta eu. Donec consectetur lacus eget urna lacinia ornare. In hac habitasse platea dictumst.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][image_with_animation image_url="109" animation="Fade In" img_link_target="_self"][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'Employee Profiles', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '105-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-05-01 23:24:53', '2015-05-01 23:24:53', '', 105, 'http://qsiodev.runq.qualcomm.com/2015/05/01/105-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
