(231, 1, '2015-05-07 18:03:53', '2015-05-07 18:03:53', '[vc_row type="full_width_background" bg_position="center center" bg_repeat="no-repeat" scene_position="center" text_color="light" text_align="left" top_padding="21%" bottom_padding="21%" id="cover" parallax_bg="true" bg_image="70"][vc_column width="1/1"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h1>Employee Profiles</h1>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row type="in_container" bg_position="left top" bg_repeat="no-repeat" scene_position="center" text_color="dark" text_align="left" id="profile1"][vc_column width="2/3" animation="none" column_padding="padding-8-percent" column_padding_position="top" background_color_opacity="1"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h2>Josef Blanz</h2>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_column_text]Josef Blanz wants to connect everyone and everything\r\n\r\nYou might say that Josef Blanz’s job is all about making the right connections. A principal engineer with QSIO Germany, Blanz leads Qualcomm’s Machine-to-Machine Communication/Internet of Things (M2M/IoT) Standards project.\r\n\r\nHis work focuses on the best way to get all sorts of machines and things connected to one another and to the Cloud. At the same time, he looks to keep communications resource-efficient and to allow simple use of network connectivity by application and product developers.\r\n\r\nIn the future, M2M and IoT markets are projected to require deployment of tens of billions of connected devices. A significant number of those devices is expected to use wireless technologies like those supported by Qualcomm.\r\n\r\n“If Qualcomm succeeds in developing features in products that makes those products the best choice when developing M2M and IoT devices, it may turn out to be a huge market for Qualcomm,” he said. “The technology being discussed and standardized in this project has the potential to impact very large markets in the future and impact our lives in a very positive way through smart grids, smart houses, connective CE, lights, appliances, smart cities, and smart vehicles.”\r\n<h3>The family vintage</h3>\r\nBorn and raised in the Pfalz region of southwest Germany, Josef now lives about 40 miles west of his birthplace in the village of Forst. It’s an area famed for wine-growing, and the wine culture – grape-growing, wine-making, and wine consumption -- is a central theme in the community’s day-to-day life. It’s even part of the Blanz family: his wife Anja grew up on a winery in Forst and her sister and brother-in-law still run the family business today.\r\n\r\nIt’s no surprise that wine-related topics run a close second to technology when Josef talks about his personal interests. “That is a must in our village,” he said. “I am not really an expert or connoisseur, but I like wine-tasting and enjoy learning more and more about wine.”\r\n\r\nHis ideal day? “Enjoying the Forster Weinfest on a nice, warm summer day with family and friends while strolling between booths and wineries enjoying good food, listening to good live music, talking with people I know well and not so well and, of course, drinking some good wine.”\r\n\r\nThe father of three children ranging in ages from 13 to 9, Josef makes sure all sorts of things are connected in his home. He set up a large touchscreen in the kitchen to control everything. He checks on his house and change settings while traveling and opens the door and gate from his phone or laptop.\r\n<h3>Hooked on BASIC as a teen-ager</h3>\r\nJosef originally set out follow in the footsteps of his father, a civil engineer. He changed career directions when, as a teen-ager, he tried his hand at BASIC programming on his father’s work computer. He was hooked, and wound up earning a degree in electrical engineering. He studied engineering at the University of Kaiserslautern, which at the time was home to one of the location of one of the world’s leading research teams on CDMA. While still an undergraduate, Josef designed a Viterbi Equalizer for the group, which led to the offer of a post-graduate position with an option to get a Ph. D., which he accepted.\r\n\r\nOne of his mentors at the university was Dr. Paul Walter Baier, one of the few CDMA experts in Germany at that time and an acquaintance of Qualcomm co-founder Andrew Viterbi.\r\n\r\n“He was a tough guy,” Josef said of Baier. “He taught me that you need to keep on working on a problem until you really get to the bottom of it and don’t give up halfway.”\r\n\r\nJosef joined Qualcomm in 1998, just as the company was trying to crack the 3GPP market and ramping up efforts to implement MTS chips. He recalls it was an uphill battle for Qualcomm to be accepted as a solid contributor interested in producing effective technology. But by a decade later, Qualcomm had become a leader in 3GPP technology.\r\n<h3>Diverse approach fits Standards group</h3>\r\nOver the years, he said the emphasis of the standards group has shifted.\r\n\r\n“Initially the focus was on 3GPP and 3GPP2, but today the set of groups we attend and work with is much more diverse,” he said.\r\n\r\nJosef is excited to be involved with wireless technology that has made it easier to stay in touch with family and friends from almost any place.\r\n\r\n“Without wireless technology I would have a very hard time traveling as much as I do,” he said. “It helps in so many situations to talk to family, to be reachable for business, to stay connected, do email, conference calls, get information off the web, all while on the go.”\r\n\r\nHis Standards project recently reached a significant milestone − Completion of a first release of specifications for M2M communications based on an M2M Service layer produced within oneM2M, a global partnership of SDOs created to support the M2M/IoT concept.\r\n\r\n“This standard has the potential to become a key enabler for larger scale M2M/IoT deployments across a number of different industry segments,” Josef said. “It may allow Qualcomm to develop products that could be sold into various industry segments or so-called verticals without the need for vertical-specific product specializations.”\r\n<h3>Building success through oneM2M</h3>\r\nJosef was a key player in the creation of oneM2M, and helped get a Qualcomm consultant Peter Nurse selected as chair of the oneM2M Technical Plenary, a move that he believes will help speed up progress in oneM2M and ensure that Qualcomm maintains a leadership role in the organization.\r\n\r\nBut as M2M/IoT gets bigger, there are more challenges. “Almost every other week you can see press releases about yet another organization that wants to cover the whole breadth and depth of M2m/IOT.\r\n\r\nThat fragmentation makes for competing groups, primarily pushed by Qualcomm competitors. The key to solving this is consolidation and a reasonable work split.\r\n\r\n“We have to stay on top of which organizations are really relevant and keep on consolidating and aligning across those in order to avoid overlap and enable interworking,” he said.\r\n\r\nPart of his challenge is overcoming skepticism from other companies when Qualcomm gets involved with a new standards organization.\r\n\r\n“Many other stakeholders suspect that we are only interested in pushing our own IPR,” he said. That sort of test arose recently in the oneM2M group when some features Qualcomm wanted specified as mandatory were watered down.\r\n\r\n“The best way to deal with such a situation is to focus on making our preferred solutions technically better and specify them in a precise manner so that using them in an implementation provides added value,” Josef said.\r\n\r\nIt takes time, he said, but after a while, individual delegates realize that Qualcomm representatives are actually quite reasonable and begin to trust that the company is interested only in designing a technically sound and proper system.\r\n\r\nHis immediate focus is on incorporating the technology specified in oneM2M with the technology Qualcomm promotes in the open source-based AllSeen Alliance and on promoting the overall value of oneM2M technology. Those efforts, Josef said, will help Qualcomm position its products for the M2M/IoT markets to make them the best choice for implementers.\r\n<h3>Setting standards for the future</h3>\r\nBlanz said it’s rewarding to work with a diverse group of people both within Qualcomm and externally.\r\n\r\n“Through the work in international and global standardization bodies, you get to know very different styles of communicating and ways of working with each other,” he said. “You get the rare opportunity to constantly improve your understanding of different cultures and mentalities. This is a very valuable skill that cannot be learned in many other jobs.”\r\n\r\nHe also appreciates the opportunity to be part of an effort that is shaping the future of M2M/IoT technology and affecting the lives of today’s generations and generations to come.\r\n\r\n“It is motivating to see – sometimes over the span of quite a few years – that a few things you have been dealing with in standards actually make it into products and ultimately affect the way we live.”[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3" animation="none" column_padding="padding-8-percent" column_padding_position="top" background_color_opacity="1"][image_with_animation image_url="157" animation="Fade In" img_link_target="_self"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row type="in_container" bg_position="left top" bg_repeat="no-repeat" scene_position="center" text_color="dark" text_align="left" id="profile2"][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h2>Rolf De Vegt</h2>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_column_text]\r\n<h4>Political approach to Standards proves successful for Rolf De Vegt</h4>\r\nAs a young man, Rolf De Vegt dreamed of growing up to become a politician in his native Netherlands. He wound up going into private business instead, but in his current role as Senior Director of Technical Standards for Qualcomm Atheros, the challenges he faces in Standards negotiations give him plenty of opportunity to put his political skills to the test.\r\n\r\n“Getting bogged down because of company political reasons can sometimes be challenging to work around,” he said. “But you just work through it, push through, making sure you make progress, finding your alliances, finding companies and individuals that have similar positions and interests, finding ways to appease or to remove barriers. That’s what the political side of Standardization is all about.”\r\n\r\nSan Jose-based De Vegt is the Standards lead for the IEEE 802.11 technologies. He also heads a Standards group for Qualcomm Atheros focused on technologies such as Bluetooth, NFC, wireless, and WLAN. Active in the Wi-Fi industry since 2001, De Vegt has chaired several key groups in the Wi-Fi Alliance. He currently serves on the Wi-Fi Alliance board of directors and chairs a committee tasked with defining Standards for devices that implement the IEEE 802.11ah standards.\r\n<h3>Steering clear of engineering</h3>\r\nRolf was born in the Netherlands, in the small town of Best south of Amsterdam, but grew up in the northern part of the country. He graduated from Nienoord College in Leek, Netherlands, and earned a master’s degree from Twente University. His degree was in public administration despite strong family ties to the engineering profession: Rolf’s father was a civil engineer and his two brothers also grew up to be engineers, one an environmental engineer for SAP and the second as a food technologist for a Dutch company.\r\n\r\nHe initially wanted to make his mark in Dutch politics but the reality of how political systems work eventually steered him in a different direction. “I probably don’t have enough patience with the slowness of the process,” he said. “But it also was having to deal with the other people in that profession.” Rolf said he’s much more comfortable working with engineers, “who aren’t so concerned with politics and perception.”\r\n\r\nHe launched his career as a management consultant, working for the Dutch Department of Finance and later for Adventis Management Consulting. But in 2001, some friends who were engineers sought to start a Wi-Fi semiconductor company and asked him to help develop a business plan. They connected with a group in the U.S. involved in a similar venture and wound up launching a startup focused on creating Wi-Fi chipsets and MIMO for the chipsets. The only non-engineer on board, he started out as a product manager, but his role evolved into handing Standards issues through his work with industry organizations such as the Wi-Fi Alliance and IEEE. He joined Qualcomm when the company, Airgo Networks, was acquired in 2006.\r\n<h3>Developing cutting-edge technology products</h3>\r\nToday, Rolf and his husband, a partner with a large accounting firm, live in San Francisco. He enjoys playing water polo, and dabbling in real estate projects in his non-working hours. He’s a frequent visitor to the nearby Sonoma wine country and enjoys traveling, especially to southeast Asia, where he spends a lot of time.\r\n\r\nIn his work with QCA, he enjoys the cutting-edge approach and constant movement of technology projects. “You’re working on something that you’ll see in the marketplace three, four, or five years from now, sometimes even seven or eight years,” he said. “You need to be forward-thinking and plot out how you can achieve what you want to achieve for your company and your team.”\r\n\r\nHis current role gives him a chance to work with content development, providing road maps and guidance for the direction in which the technologies will evolve. He focuses on identifying what kind of market opportunities the company should go after and how technologies can fit in a market or consumer needs context. “That’s where I can add a lot of value,” Rolf said.\r\n\r\nStill, there are challenges ahead when it comes to setting Wi-Fi standards, principally the growing strength of Asian companies, especially in China. “That’s a trend we have to deal with,” he said. “Qualcomm is doing well on the competitive side. That means our competition is getting nervous and lashing out more.”\r\n<h3>Driving the Standards evolution</h3>\r\nRolf said the best part of his work in Standards is the chance “to work with really smart people and to create opportunities for Qualcomm to compete. A lot of our work is driven by Standards and Standards evolution, and a lot of opportunities are created by that,” he said.\r\n\r\nRolf’s team has been successful in pushing through standards for IEEE 802.11ah technology, a key for enabling the Internet of Things (IoT). “It’s a new standard that allows for very low power consumption and very long range that targets battery-operated devices in homes and other locations. That’s been primarily driven by Qualcomm and Qualcomm engineers, and I think that’s a huge achievement.” He’s also working to make sure the Wi-Fi interoperability program for the 802.11ah Standards launches. The Wi-Fi Alliance group Rolf chairs is defining the program, and he’s driving the activity for the organization.\r\n\r\n“I want to make sure that 12 months from now, we’ve made a lot of progress on that and that we are on our way to building a forceful ecosystem around that particular Standard.” He predicts the emergence of this new technology will create additional opportunities for Qualcomm down the road.\r\n<h3>New opportunity in multiuser MIMO</h3>\r\nThanks in part to Rolf’s influence, the Wi-Fi Alliance also is moving ahead with an IEEE 802.11ac Standards program, which will launch a new technology called multiuser MIMO. “The whole transition to multiuser MIMO is creating all kinds of advantages for our products here at Qualcomm Atheros,” he said. “We are probably the first in the market, so the opportunity has been created by the standard and the Wi-Fi Alliance program.”\r\n\r\nBy executing on time with its products, QCA has gained a large share in the enterprise and consumer Wi-Fi markets. “It positions us better in the whole emerging IoT and wearables market with a fresh new technology,” Rolf said\r\n\r\nLooking ahead, Rolf predicts a major transition in the Wi-Fi industry over the emerging IEEE 802.11ax technology. “We want to make sure that we have a key role in defining what’s going to be in that Standard,” he said. “That’s important both from a timeline management standpoint, but also from an IP content perspective.” Those Standards, Rolf said, will provide an opportunity for Qualcomm to expand its leadership in Wi-Fi in the handheld device market.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][image_with_animation image_url="158" animation="Fade In" img_link_target="_self"][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'Employee Profiles', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '105-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-07 18:03:53', '2015-05-07 18:03:53', '', 105, 'http://qsiodev.runq.qualcomm.com/2015/05/07/105-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
